issue.body:
This issue tracker is for bug reports only. **If you want to request troubleshooting assistance with Outline Manager or Outline Client, please do not submit a bug here. Instead, please contact us using our [support website](https://support.getoutline.org/s/contactsupport).** Developers using Outline SDK, please post your questions on the [SDK Discussion board](https://github.com/Jigsaw-Code/outline-sdk/discussions).

**Describe the bug**
nothing can be clicked in the menu bar icon on macos sonoma

**To reproduce**
download macos sonoma
click the outline logo in the taskbar

**Expected behavior**
to be able to use the app

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Client system (please complete the following information):**
 - Outline Client Version: latest app store version
 -  - Your Operating System: latest macos

**Submit feedback**
Please submit feedback through the app and label it with this issue number.

Add any other context about the problem here.

comment.body: Hi @brandons209 , I apologize for the inconvenience, but due to limited staffing, we are only officially supporting the Ubuntu distribution of Linux at this time. We have developed a command line interface for Outline VPN here: https://github.com/Jigsaw-Code/outline-sdk/tree/main/x/examples/outline-cli. Please feel free to try it on Kali Linux and contribute to the project if you encounter any issues. Thanks.

comment.body:
RE: that third point. That shouldn't be the responsibility of the individual views at all imo. We should do that at a layer above the individual views at the page layout level in app-root. This isn't actually solving that issue (though how I had it before also didn't solve that of course, we need a larger change to move those layout concerns to app-root). So something like:

```
<main>
  <iron-pages>
    <individual view1 />
    <individual view2 />
  </iron-pages>
</main>
```

Instead of what we have now:

```
<iron-pages>
  <individual view1>
    <main />
  </individual view1>
  <individual view2>
    <main />
  </individual view2>
<iron-pages>
```

comment.body:
Done, though I'm not a big fan of violating separation of concerns this way. HTML elements should only serve a structural purpose, not a style one.

What side effects you are worried about that wouldn't also apply to a container element? The universal selector isn't all that special; I've never run into issues with proper style encapsulation.
